<http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4776699>
        a                        fabio:Figure ;
        dc:description           "FIGURE 7. A–F. Hormoscilla irregularis Novis & Visnovsky (photographed from culture LCR-OSC2; light micrographs). A. Long trichome showing short cells with constrictions between them. B. Typical morphology with arrangement of trichomes into segments of cells, with irregular lateral position. C. Trichomes become truncated by fragmentation and dissolving of the sheath. D. False branching through trichome fragmentation (during which necridic cells occur, as indicated by arrow). E. False branching by trichome overlap. F. Release of hormogonia. G–M. Phormidium arthurensis Novis & Visnovsky (photographed from culture LCR-OSC4, G–K light micrographs, L–M transmission electron micrographs). G. Mature trichome with rounded end cell, and arrangement into cell segments (arrows between the segments). H. Trichome with fragmented end, in which the sheath is visible (arrow). I. Prior to fragmentation, the cell segments become pronounced. J. A hormogone released from this fragmentation. K. Development of the new trichome (arrow) is isopolar. L, M. Cells in transverse section showing sheath (s) and thylakoid membranes (tm), which are peripheral and tightly packed, and may be somewhat curved (M). Scales: 10 µm in F (use in A–K), 1 µm in L (use in L–M)." ;
        fabio:hasRepresentation  "https://zenodo.org/record/4776699/files/figure.png" .
